  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I prevent iMovie for iPad from cropping the top and bottom off my video that was originally taken in portrait orientation?",
  "response": "If you're experiencing cropping issues with videos taken in portrait orientation in iMovie for iPad, here are some steps you can take to prevent this from happening:\n\n1. **Change Project Settings**: When you start a new project in iMovie, make sure to choose the project settings that match your video or to set it in a way that accommodates vertical videos.\n\n   - Open iMovie and create a new project.\n   - When the project opens, ensure that you rotate your video to match the portrait orientation by tapping on the video clip in the timeline and then using the rotation tool. \n   \n2. **Check the Video Size**: Ensure the original video is not too narrow for the standard aspect ratio being used in your project. \n\n3. **Use Picture-in-Picture (PIP) or Cutaway Option**: If you do want to include the video in a standard landscape format but want to avoid cropping:\n\n   - Select the video clip in the timeline.\n   - Tap on the video overlay settings (the button that looks like two overlapping squares).\n   - Choose the \"Picture in Picture\" option or \"Cutaway.\" This allows you to maintain the full vertical video while adjusting how it fits within the landscape project.\n\n4. **Adjust the Clip**: You can manually adjust the size and position of the video clip in the viewing window:\n   \n   - Select the video clip in the timeline.\n   - Use pinch or drag gestures to resize or reposition the video within the frame. This way, you can keep your important visual elements in the frame without cropping.\n\n5. **Export the Video in Different Aspect Ratio**: If you plan to share the video on social media, consider exporting it in a vertical format if supported by the platform, which can help maintain the original look and feel of your portrait video.\n\n6. **Third-party Apps**: If iMovie continues to cause issues, consider using other video editing apps that provide better support for vertical videos. Apps like InShot or Adobe Premiere Rush allow more control over different orientations.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to prevent iMovie from cropping your portrait videos.",
